The current situation is, as in Jesus’ days, where Roman Caesars or Kings demanded steep taxes beyond what ordinary mwananchi could bear.This Christmas, and as we move towards 2021, let us think ahead as a nation on how to raise our GDP. Never has a more unique Christmas than this been experienced, with the economy reported to be at its worst amid a global pandemic. The Kenya National Bureau of Statistics indicates that Kenya’s Gross Domestic Product (GDP) fell by 5.7 per cent between January and March, compared to a growth of 4.9 per cent in the same period last year, in which an overall expansion of 5.3 per cent was marked. That poverty is biting is not in doubt.



