It’s a time no different than the days of Jesus Christ, whose birth Christians are celebrating. Born in a manger, where cows, smelly sheep and other livestock dwell, resources were difficult to come by. Jesus, a carpenter’s son, born in such paucity, regularly spoke of poverty in sayings such as: “The poor you shall always have with you.”
Not surprisingly, most widely held and understood definition of absolute poverty is measured strictly in economic terms. Arguably, if the average Kenyan earns less than $1.9 a day, approximately Sh211, then paradoxically, poverty fits the bill. This amounts to approximately Sh6,330 a month. It is deplorable to imagine a chief income earner expected to feed his or her family with such earnings.





Kenya and Singapore
The Christmas story marked with penury and sheer squalor holds relevance in our times. That Jesus’ parents could not afford a hospital birth or a nice facility is shameful and speaks of the abject poverty experienced in that day. It’s sad to think that many Kenyan families will go without a decent meal this Christmas, a narrative requiring turnaround.
Economists often compare Kenya and Singapore as they both attained independence in 1963. Research Journal of Finance and Accounting, comparing Singapore and Kenya, records: “Ironically Singapore is an emerging third world economy with its GDP over seven times the Kenyan GDP”. As per this 2011 statistic, Singapore’s GDP was estimated at over Sh20 trillion and Kenya’s at Sh2.8 trillion. Unlike Singapore, Kenya is still characterised by high rates of unemployment, poverty, poor housing and healthcare and low life expectancy.



