The current situation is, as in Jesus’ days, where Roman Caesars or Kings demanded steep taxes beyond what ordinary mwananchi could bear. The difference with Jesus’ earthly dad being a carpenter, was perhaps in earning a “salary” that sustained his family, as we hear not of impoverishment or deterioration, in Christ’s upbringing. We also know from Holy writings, that Jesus had other siblings born after him and thus he was part of a sizeable family.
The point: Families will continue to grow! But unlike our former peer Singapore with a GDP that allows for the healthcare and pension needs of their population to be met, we cannot guarantee the same to our people.
The story from a wise chap, King Solomon, through whose lineage Jesus was born, provides the answer to poverty: “Money is the answer to all things.” Ecclesiastes 10:19 Think of it. To get treatment in hospital, participate in politics, run a business and educate children, money is key.
This Christmas, and as we move towards 2021, let us think ahead as a nation on how to raise our GDP. When Kenya shines, we all shine. Being dubbed poor; unable to sustain our own is not a compliment.



