Basic needs
While many travel up-country amidst hiked fares in a strained economy, this too, is bothersome. Will there be merry making or murmuring? Will there be enough for example to eat? While an old and thorny matter, no one ever desires to be poor.
The change in mindset for Jesus’ followers has been profoundly substituted with understanding of economic principle: to seek first God’s Kingdom and all these things — basic needs — will be met. So, while troubles face countless, faceless Kenyans, the Christmas story ends in resurrection, thus holding out hope.
Love cured all because it selflessly gave the Christmas child up for crucifixion. Love cares. Love shares. I pen a note of wishing you a blessed Christmas with a reminder of the entrepreneur, Muhammad Yunus’ words: “Poverty does not belong in civilised human society. Its proper place is in a museum.”
